### rag - explain RAG retrieval augmented generation
grade: **A** (content A, time penalty 0) - 50.9s vs 60s target
plan: 1 step(s) - research.deep=ok/38941ms

```
**Retrieval‑Augmented Generation (RAG)** is a two‑stage architecture that makes large‑language‑model (LLM) answers more factual and up‑to‑date by first pulling relevant external information and then using that information to guide generation.

| Stage | What happens | Key components |
|-------|--------------|----------------|
| **Retrieval** | The user query is encoded into a vector and matched against a **vector database** of pre‑computed embeddings of documents (or API results, knowledge‑base entries, etc.). The top‑k most similar chunks are returned. | • External knowledge source (documents, APIs)  <br>• Text chunking & preprocessing  <br>• Embedding model  <br>• Vector DB  <br>• Query en
```

